<section class="stories-section">
  <div class="container">
    
    <div class="story-item">
      <h3>The Lost Princess</h3>
      <p>
        Once, there was a king who had six sons and one daughter. The daughter was very precious in his eyes. One time, while he was together with her, he became angry and blurted out, "May the Not Good One take you away." At night she disappeared. The Second to the King searched for her for many years through deserts and forests until he found her in a castle of "not good."
      </p>
      <p>
        To rescue her, he had to remain in one place for a full year, longing to rescue her. But through tests of refraining from eating and sleep, he ultimately succeeded through his unwavering determination.
      </p>
      <p class="na-nach-signature">נַ נַחְ נַחְמָ נַחְמָן מאוּמָן</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-item">
      <h3>The Turkey Prince</h3>
      <p>
        A parable about a prince who fell into a psychosis that he was a turkey. He would sit naked underneath the table and drag bits of bread and bones like a turkey. All the doctors despaired of helping him.
      </p>
      <p>
        Until a sage came along who undressed himself and sat next to the prince, gradually adding clothing back - shirt, pants, other garments - each time saying, "You think a turkey cannot wear this? It is possible!" until he healed him completely.
      </p>
      <div class="quote-box">
        <p><em>The referent is understandable to those with understanding: A person who desires to draw close to the service of Hashem is like a turkey dressed in materialism, and in this fashion it is possible, little by little, to draw himself close.</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="story-item">
      <h3>The Treasure Under the Bridge</h3>
      <p>
        A story he told of a man who dreamt that in Vienna, under a bridge there is a treasure. He traveled there and met a soldier. The soldier told him he had also dreamt of a treasure under a bridge in a certain city. The man realized: the treasure was by him all along - but to know of it, he needed to travel to Vienna.
      </p>
      <p class="na-nach-signature">נַ נַחְ נַחְמָ נַחְמָן מאוּמָן</p>
      <div class="quote-box">
        <p><em>"So it is in the matter of serving Hashem: the treasure is by each one by himself, but in order to know of the treasure it is incumbent to travel to the tzaddik."</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="story-item">
      <h3>The Flood</h3>
      <p>
        Rabbainu told a parable of a king who went hunting, dressed as a commoner. Suddenly heavy rain fell - a flood. All the ministers scattered to save themselves, but a villager saved the king, gave him food, and let him sleep by the oven.
      </p>
      <p>
        The king said, "Since you saved me, you will bring me in your wagon and seat me on the royal throne."
      </p>
      <div class="quote-box">
        <p><em>"At the heels of the Messiah there will be a flood - they will shoot with heresy... Even in the Land of Israel it will splash into kosher hearts, and with wisdoms no remedy will be given. Just the simple Jews who recite Psalms with simplicity... when the Messiah comes they will place the crown on his head."</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="story-item">
      <h3>The Tainted Grain</h3>
      <p>
        A king saw that all the grain that would grow would make whoever eats from it become crazy. His advisor suggested they eat from it too and mark their foreheads so at least they would know they were crazy.
      </p>
      <p>
        This parable teaches that even if the whole world is caught in vanities, one must be strong to engage only in Torah and mitzvos, even if appearing crazy to others.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-item">
      <h3>One Thing Brought the Success</h3>
      <div class="quote-box">
        <p><em>"With one thing I was successful, and through this I merited to what I merited..."</em></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        Rabbi Nachman said that Adam HaRishon, when he ate from the Tree of Knowledge, all the souls tasted, but Rabbi Nachman's holy soul merited that it did not taste from the Tree of Knowledge whatsoever.
      </p>
      <p class="na-nach-signature">נַ נַחְ נַחְמָ נַחְמָן מאוּמָן</p>
    </div>

